The honest framing
What you're describing is essentially a lightweight tiling window manager that spawns/hosts terminal emulators. There are two fundamentally different architectures, and picking the wrong one will cost you an order of magnitude in performance.

Option A: Native macOS (the speed answer)
Swift + AppKit, spawning PTYs directly. No Electron, no web layer, no cross-platform abstraction.

Window management: Use NSWindow for real windows, or a single NSWindow with custom NSView tiles if you want it to feel like one app. For actual tiling of other windows, you'd use the Accessibility API (this is how yabai, Rectangle, and Amethyst work).
Terminal rendering: Use SwiftTerm (the well-maintained Swift port of xterm.js) or write directly against a PTY using forkpty() and render with Metal/CoreText. SwiftTerm gets you 90% there with near-native speed.
Why it's fast: Direct GPU compositing via Metal, zero IPC overhead for rendering, AppKit windows are already the fastest thing the OS can draw, and PTY handling is a syscall away.
Realistic performance: sub-16ms frame times trivially, cold start under 200ms, memory footprint ~30-60MB for six terminals.

Option B: Cross-platform (the pragmatic answer)
You have a spectrum here, ordered by performance:

Rust + wgpu + a Rust terminal crate (like alacritty_terminal as a library). This is what Zellij and Wezterm do. Performance is genuinely excellent — Alacritty is GPU-accelerated and arguably faster than Terminal.app. Cross-platform cost is near zero at runtime.
Tauri (Rust backend + webview frontend). Uses the system webview (WKWebView on macOS), so much lighter than Electron. Good for the UI chrome, but you'd still want native PTY handling in the Rust side and a WebGL terminal renderer like xterm.js. Noticeably slower than option 1.
Electron. Don't. You said max speed.
