The mental model first
The whole app is a loop: PTYs produce bytes → terminal state machines consume them → a renderer draws the current state 60 times a second → input events flow back to the focused PTY. Everything else is organization around that loop.

The architecture I'd recommend has three concurrency domains:

The main thread owns winit's event loop (required on macOS), wgpu, and all rendering. It reads from shared state, never writes application logic.
A tokio runtime owns all PTY I/O. One task per PTY, reading bytes and pushing into the terminal state machine.
A message bus connects them. UI events go one way, render-dirty signals go the other.
This is cleaner than it sounds and it keeps you out of the two traps that kill Rust GUI projects: blocking the render thread on I/O, and lock contention between readers and the renderer.

Crate structure
I'd split this into a workspace with several crates from day one. Not because it's a big project yet, but because the boundaries force good design and compile times stay sane:

focusterm/
├── Cargo.toml                  # workspace root
├── crates/
│   ├── focusterm-core/         # domain types, no I/O, no rendering
│   ├── focusterm-pty/          # PTY management, async readers
│   ├── focusterm-render/       # wgpu + glyphon rendering
│   ├── focusterm-ui/           # strip, cards, input handling, layout
│   └── focusterm-app/          # binary: ties everything together
└── assets/
    └── fonts/
Why this split: core has no dependencies on wgpu, winit, or tokio. You can unit-test layout math, workspace logic, and state transitions without spinning up a GPU. pty depends on core and tokio. render depends on core, wgpu, glyphon. ui depends on core, winit, render. app is the only crate that knows about all of them.

