The render pipeline
The fundamental question: how do you go from a grid of terminal cells to pixels on screen, 60+ times a second, for up to six terminals simultaneously?

The frame, end to end
A single frame does this:

Acquire the surface texture from wgpu. This blocks briefly if the GPU is behind; usually instant.
Compute tile rectangles from the current layout and window size. Pure math, microseconds.
For each visible tile, snapshot its terminal grid. Lock the Term, copy the visible rows into a local Vec<RenderCell>, release. This is the only place the render thread touches shared state.
Build the frame's draw data. Background quads per cell (for non-default backgrounds), glyph runs for text, cursor quad, tile border quads, selection overlay if any.
One render pass, multiple pipelines. Draw backgrounds, then text, then overlays (cursor, selection, borders). Then egui on top.
Submit and present.
The performance discipline is: steps 3 and 4 run on the main thread with no allocations in the hot path, step 5 is where the GPU does the work.

The cell snapshot
Here's the shape you want:

