#[derive(Copy, Clone)]
struct RenderCell {
    ch: char,
    fg: [u8; 4],
    bg: [u8; 4],
    flags: CellFlags,  // bold, italic, underline, inverse, etc.
}

struct TileSnapshot {
    cells: Vec<RenderCell>,  // row-major, cols * rows
    cols: u16,
    rows: u16,
    cursor: Option<(u16, u16)>,
    cursor_style: CursorStyle,
}
Preallocate these. Keep one TileSnapshot per tile, reuse across frames, clear() and refill each frame. Zero allocations during steady-state rendering is the goal and it's achievable.

The snapshot pass looks like:

rust
fn snapshot_tile(tile: &Tile, snapshot: &mut TileSnapshot) {
    let term = tile.term.lock();  // parking_lot, fast path ~20ns uncontended
    let grid = term.grid();
    let display_offset = grid.display_offset();
    
    snapshot.cells.clear();
    snapshot.cols = grid.columns() as u16;
    snapshot.rows = grid.screen_lines() as u16;
    
    for row_idx in 0..snapshot.rows {
        let line = &grid[Line(row_idx as i32 - display_offset as i32)];
        for cell in line.iter() {
            snapshot.cells.push(RenderCell {
                ch: cell.c,
                fg: convert_color(cell.fg),
                bg: convert_color(cell.bg),
                flags: convert_flags(cell.flags),
            });
        }
    }
    
    snapshot.cursor = if term.mode().contains(TermMode::SHOW_CURSOR) {
        Some((term.grid().cursor.point.column.0 as u16,
              term.grid().cursor.point.line.0 as u16))
    } else {
        None
    };
    // lock released here
}
The lock is held for the duration of the copy, which for an 80×24 terminal is ~2000 cells of simple struct copies — nanoseconds. For a giant 300×100 terminal it's ~30k cells, still well under a millisecond. The PTY reader will never notice.

The rendering strategy: quads + glyphs
Two GPU pipelines, both simple:

Background pipeline. Instanced quads. One instance per cell that has a non-default background. Vertex shader takes instance data (cell x, y, width, height, color), fragment shader outputs the color. This is the fastest possible draw path on any GPU — you'll easily push a million cells per second.

Text pipeline. Glyphon handles this. You build a Buffer of text per tile, set its position, and glyphon rasterizes glyphs into an atlas and issues draw calls. Under the hood it's also instanced quads, just with texture sampling.

The sequence per frame:

rust
fn render_frame(&mut self, state: &AppState) -> Result<()> {
    let output = self.surface.get_current_texture()?;
    let view = output.texture.create_view(&Default::default());
    
    // Compute layout
    let tile_rects = compute_tile_rects(&state.active_workspace().layout, 
                                         self.window_size);
    
    // Snapshot all tiles (holds locks briefly)
    for (tile, rect) in state.active_workspace().tiles.iter().zip(&tile_rects) {
        snapshot_tile(tile, &mut self.snapshots[tile.id]);
    }
    
    // Build draw data
    self.bg_quads.clear();
    for (snapshot, rect) in self.snapshots.iter().zip(&tile_rects) {
        build_bg_quads(snapshot, rect, &self.cell_metrics, &mut self.bg_quads);
    }
    
    // Build glyphon buffers  
    for (snapshot, rect) in self.snapshots.iter().zip(&tile_rects) {
        update_text_buffer(snapshot, rect, &mut self.text_buffers[tile_idx], 
                          &mut self.font_system);
    }
    
    // Prepare glyphon for this frame
    self.text_renderer.prepare(
        &self.device, &self.queue, &mut self.font_system,
        &mut self.atlas, /* viewport */, 
        self.text_buffers.iter().map(|b| TextArea { /* ... */ }),
        &mut self.swash_cache,
    )?;
    
    let mut encoder = self.device.create_command_encoder(&Default::default());
    {
        let mut pass = encoder.begin_render_pass(&wgpu::RenderPassDescriptor {
            color_attachments: &[Some(wgpu::RenderPassColorAttachment {
                view: &view,
                resolve_target: None,
                ops: wgpu::Operations {
                    load: wgpu::LoadOp::Clear(self.bg_color),
                    store: wgpu::StoreOp::Store,
                },
            })],
            ..Default::default()
        });
        
        // 1. Cell backgrounds
        self.quad_pipeline.draw(&mut pass, &self.bg_quads);
        
        // 2. Text
        self.text_renderer.render(&self.atlas, /* viewport */, &mut pass)?;
        
        // 3. Cursor and selection overlays
        self.quad_pipeline.draw(&mut pass, &self.overlay_quads);
        
        // 4. Tile borders
        self.quad_pipeline.draw(&mut pass, &self.border_quads);
        
        // 5. egui on top (covered in next section)
        self.egui_renderer.render(&mut pass, /* ... */);
    }
    
    self.queue.submit(Some(encoder.finish()));
    output.present();
    
    Ok(())
}
Note the single render pass. Starting and ending render passes has nontrivial overhead on some backends (especially Metal), so batching everything into one pass matters.

Font metrics and cell grid
This is where "fast Rust terminals" diverge from "good Rust terminals." The cell grid is the foundation of everything: every cell is the same width, rows are uniform height, and glyphs must be centered within their cells consistently.

Compute this once at startup and on font change:

rust
struct CellMetrics {
    width: f32,       // advance width of 'M' in the monospace font
    height: f32,      // line height
    ascent: f32,      // baseline offset from top
    descent: f32,
}
Use the metrics of a reference glyph (typically M or 0) as the cell width. For CJK characters that are double-width, render them spanning two cells and skip the next cell. Alacritty's terminal grid already marks these with a WIDE_CHAR flag — honor it.

A subtlety: ligatures break the cell grid. => in Fira Code becomes a single glyph spanning two cells. You have two choices — disable ligatures (what Alacritty does, controversially) or handle them specially (what Wezterm does, complicated). I'd disable in v1 and make it a config option in v2. Users who care will tell you.

Dirty tracking and the "render only what changed" trap
Obvious optimization: only redraw tiles that changed. Seductive, and mostly a waste for your use case. Here's why.

A Claude Code session emits output continuously during generation. A shell running cargo watch emits output on every file save. htop refreshes every second. In practice, at any given moment something is dirty, and checking dirtiness per tile adds complexity for minimal gain.

The better strategy: redraw the whole window at up to 60fps, but only when something has changed. Track a single needs_redraw boolean. PTY events set it, input events set it, animations set it. If it's false at the end of an event loop iteration, control_flow = ControlFlow::Wait. You get 0% CPU when idle and 60fps when active. This is what most terminals do and it's the right tradeoff.

The one refinement: when output is arriving at extreme rates (yes piped to itself), cap redraws at 60fps regardless of event rate. Otherwise you'll process 10,000 PTY events per frame and starve the renderer. A simple frame budget check in the event loop handles this.

Color and theming
alacritty_terminal reports colors as Color::Named(NamedColor), Color::Spec(Rgb), or Color::Indexed(u8). You need a color palette to resolve named and indexed colors:

rust
struct Theme {
    foreground: Rgb,
    background: Rgb,
    cursor: Rgb,
    ansi: [Rgb; 16],         // the 16 ANSI colors
    bright_ansi: [Rgb; 16],  // bright variants
}

fn resolve(color: alacritty_terminal::vte::ansi::Color, theme: &Theme) -> [u8; 4] {
    use alacritty_terminal::vte::ansi::{Color, NamedColor};
    match color {
        Color::Named(NamedColor::Foreground) => theme.foreground.into_rgba(),
        Color::Named(NamedColor::Background) => theme.background.into_rgba(),
        Color::Named(NamedColor::Red) => theme.ansi[1].into_rgba(),
        // ... etc
        Color::Spec(rgb) => [rgb.r, rgb.g, rgb.b, 255],
        Color::Indexed(i) if i < 16 => theme.ansi[i as usize].into_rgba(),
        Color::Indexed(i) => xterm_256_color(i).into_rgba(),  // standard table
    }
}
Ship with good defaults. Tokyo Night, Catppuccin Mocha, and Solarized Dark are the unofficial "you ship a terminal, you ship these" list. Let users supply their own via config.

egui integration
Now the UI layer. The interesting question: how do egui and your wgpu terminal renderer share the same window without fighting?

The integration pattern
Use egui-wgpu (the official egui backend for wgpu) and egui-winit (the official event bridge). The pattern is well-established:

rust
struct UiLayer {
    egui_ctx: egui::Context,
    egui_winit: egui_winit::State,
    egui_renderer: egui_wgpu::Renderer,
}

impl UiLayer {
    fn new(window: &Window, device: &wgpu::Device, 
           surface_format: wgpu::TextureFormat) -> Self {
        let egui_ctx = egui::Context::default();
        let egui_winit = egui_winit::State::new(
            egui_ctx.clone(), egui::ViewportId::ROOT, window, None, None, None,
        );
        let egui_renderer = egui_wgpu::Renderer::new(
            device, surface_format, None, 1, false,
        );
        Self { egui_ctx, egui_winit, egui_renderer }
    }
    
    fn handle_event(&mut self, window: &Window, event: &WindowEvent) -> bool {
        // Returns true if egui consumed the event
        self.egui_winit.on_window_event(window, event).consumed
    }
}
Every frame, between your terminal rendering and presenting, you run the egui pass:

rust
// In render_frame, after terminal drawing, before submit:

let raw_input = self.ui.egui_winit.take_egui_input(&self.window);
let full_output = self.ui.egui_ctx.run(raw_input, |ctx| {
    draw_ui(ctx, state, &mut actions);  // your UI code
});

self.ui.egui_winit.handle_platform_output(&self.window, full_output.platform_output);

let tris = self.ui.egui_ctx.tessellate(full_output.shapes, 
                                         full_output.pixels_per_point);

for (id, delta) in &full_output.textures_delta.set {
    self.ui.egui_renderer.update_texture(&self.device, &self.queue, *id, delta);
}

self.ui.egui_renderer.update_buffers(&self.device, &self.queue, &mut encoder, 
                                      &tris, &screen_descriptor);

// In the same render pass as terminals, after terminal draws:
self.ui.egui_renderer.render(&mut pass, &tris, &screen_descriptor);

for id in &full_output.textures_delta.free {
    self.ui.egui_renderer.free_texture(id);
}
The key insight: egui draws on top of your terminals in the same render pass. It uses alpha blending, so you can have semi-transparent overlays (settings panels, dialogs) and they'll composite correctly over the terminal grid.

Event routing: the critical decision
Input events are the hardest part. Who gets each event — egui or the focused terminal? The correct order:

First, offer the event to egui. If egui's on_window_event returns consumed: true, stop. The user clicked on the strip or is typing in a rename field.
Otherwise, if it's a keyboard event, route to the focused tile's PTY.
Otherwise, if it's a mouse event within a terminal's bounds, handle terminal mouse interaction (selection, scroll, click-through focus).
Otherwise, let the event loop handle it (window resize, close, etc.).
The subtlety: focus. egui has its own focus model for its widgets. Your tiles have a focus model for which one gets keystrokes. These must not conflict. The rule: if egui reports a widget has focus (text field being edited), egui gets keystrokes. Otherwise, the focused tile does.

rust
fn route_keyboard(&mut self, event: &KeyEvent) {
    if self.ui.egui_ctx.wants_keyboard_input() {
        // egui has a focused text field; it already got the event
        return;
    }
    
    if let Some(tile_id) = self.app_state.focused_tile {
        self.pty_manager.send_key(tile_id, event);
    }
}
wants_keyboard_input() and wants_pointer_input() are your two main coordination functions. Use them religiously.

Drawing the strip
The strip is pure egui — a TopBottomPanel::top with custom-painted cards inside. Here's the sketch:

rust
fn draw_strip(ctx: &egui::Context, state: &AppState, actions: &mut Vec<Action>) {
    egui::TopBottomPanel::top("workspace_strip")
        .exact_height(56.0)
        .frame(egui::Frame::none().fill(ctx.style().visuals.window_fill))
        .show(ctx, |ui| {
            ui.horizontal(|ui| {
                for (idx, workspace) in state.workspaces.iter().enumerate() {
                    draw_card(ui, workspace, 
                             idx == state.active_workspace_idx(), 
                             actions);
                }
                
                // "+" button to add workspace
                if ui.add(egui::Button::new("+").min_size(egui::vec2(32.0, 48.0))).clicked() {
                    actions.push(Action::CreateWorkspace);
                }
            });
        });
}

fn draw_card(ui: &mut egui::Ui, workspace: &Workspace, is_active: bool, 
             actions: &mut Vec<Action>) {
    let card_size = egui::vec2(140.0, 48.0);
    let (rect, response) = ui.allocate_exact_size(card_size, 
                                                   egui::Sense::click_and_drag());
    
    let painter = ui.painter();
    let bg_color = if is_active { 
        ui.style().visuals.selection.bg_fill 
    } else { 
        ui.style().visuals.widgets.inactive.bg_fill 
    };
    painter.rect_filled(rect, 6.0, bg_color);
    
    // Draw label
    painter.text(
        rect.left_top() + egui::vec2(8.0, 6.0),
        egui::Align2::LEFT_TOP,
        &workspace.label,
        egui::FontId::proportional(13.0),
        ui.style().visuals.text_color(),
    );
    
    // Draw mini tile indicators
    let indicator_y = rect.bottom() - 12.0;
    for (i, tile) in workspace.tiles.iter().enumerate().take(6) {
        let x = rect.left() + 8.0 + (i as f32) * 10.0;
        let dot_color = if tile.has_new_output {
            egui::Color32::from_rgb(100, 200, 100)
        } else {
            ui.style().visuals.weak_text_color()
        };
        painter.circle_filled(egui::pos2(x, indicator_y), 3.0, dot_color);
    }
    
    if response.clicked() {
        actions.push(Action::SwitchWorkspace(workspace.id));
    }
    
    if response.double_clicked() {
        actions.push(Action::StartRenaming(workspace.id));
    }
}
This is illustrative — real code gets fiddlier with hover states, drag visualization, and accessibility. But the shape is right: egui gives you primitives (allocate_exact_size, painter, Sense::click_and_drag), and you compose them.

Drag and drop: the fun part
This is where egui earns its keep. Built-in drag handling is ergonomic:

rust
// In the tile being dragged:
let response = ui.interact(tile_rect, tile_id, egui::Sense::drag());

if response.drag_started() {
    ui.ctx().set_dragged_id(tile_id);
    // Store what's being dragged (e.g., in a resource)
    ui.ctx().memory_mut(|mem| {
        mem.data.insert_temp(egui::Id::new("dragged_tile"), tile.id);
    });
}

if response.dragged() {
    // Draw a ghost following the cursor
    if let Some(pos) = ui.ctx().pointer_interact_pos() {
        let painter = ui.ctx().layer_painter(egui::LayerId::new(
            egui::Order::Tooltip, egui::Id::new("drag_ghost")
        ));
        painter.rect_filled(
            egui::Rect::from_center_size(pos, egui::vec2(120.0, 80.0)),
            4.0,
            egui::Color32::from_rgba_premultiplied(100, 100, 100, 180),
        );
    }
}

// In the drop target (a workspace card):
if response.hovered() && ui.ctx().dragged_id().is_some() {
    // Highlight the card as drop target
    painter.rect_stroke(rect, 6.0, egui::Stroke::new(2.0, egui::Color32::WHITE));
}

if response.drag_stopped_on(card_id) {
    if let Some(tile_id) = ui.ctx().memory(|mem| 
        mem.data.get_temp::<TileId>(egui::Id::new("dragged_tile"))
    ) {
        actions.push(Action::MoveTile { 
            tile_id, 
            target_workspace: workspace.id 
        });
    }
}
egui handles the event plumbing (mouse down, move, up across widgets) — you just declare intent.

The action pattern
Notice I keep passing actions: &mut Vec<Action> around. This is deliberate. UI code should never mutate AppState directly — that creates a tangle where the UI is reading state that it's simultaneously modifying, and it makes testing impossible.

Instead, UI draws against a read-only &AppState, pushes Actions into a vec, and after the UI pass completes, you drain the vec and apply each action to the state:

rust
pub enum Action {
    SwitchWorkspace(WorkspaceId),
    CreateWorkspace,
    RenameWorkspace { id: WorkspaceId, new_label: String },
    MoveTile { tile_id: TileId, target_workspace: WorkspaceId },
    FocusTile(TileId),
    CloseTile(TileId),
    SetLayout(Layout),
    ToggleZenMode,
    ToggleFollowMode(TileId),
    // ...
}

fn apply_action(state: &mut AppState, pty_manager: &mut PtyManager, action: Action) {
    match action {
        Action::SwitchWorkspace(id) => {
            state.active_workspace = id;
            // update focused tile if needed
        }
        Action::MoveTile { tile_id, target_workspace } => {
            let tile = state.remove_tile(tile_id);
            state.workspace_mut(target_workspace).tiles.push(tile);
        }
        // ...
    }
}
This pattern gives you three free things: every user interaction is a serializable event (hello, undo/redo and session replay); state mutations are localized to one function (easy to audit); testing is trivial (construct state, apply action, assert).

The visual polish pass
egui's defaults are functional but not beautiful. Budget time for a style pass once the app works. Key knobs:

ctx.style_mut().visuals.widgets.* — control colors for inactive/hovered/active widgets
ctx.style_mut().spacing.item_spacing — tighten or loosen layout
Custom fonts via ctx.set_fonts — match your terminal font family for the strip, or use a UI font
Frame::none().fill(...).rounding(...) — card backgrounds with rounded corners
Animation via ctx.request_repaint_after(Duration::from_millis(16)) during transitions
The goal: the strip should feel like it belongs with the terminals, not like a generic immediate-mode GUI slapped on top. This is mostly matching colors and spacing to your terminal theme.

Performance notes on egui
egui re-tessellates every frame. For a simple strip with 5-10 cards, this is nothing — sub-millisecond. It becomes a concern if you put the entire terminal rendering inside egui (don't) or if you have hundreds of animated widgets (you won't). For your design, egui's overhead will be 0.5-2ms per frame, which is invisible at 60fps.

One gotcha: egui continuously repaints while the mouse is over an interactive widget. This prevents your "idle at 0% CPU" goal when the cursor is in the strip. This is usually fine (the cursor isn't in the strip most of the time), but if it bothers you, you can override with ctx.request_repaint_after logic.

