Git worktrees per tile: the design
This is actually the killer feature for the Claude Code use case. Here's why it fits: you often want to let Claude work on a feature while you continue on main, or run three Claude sessions exploring three different approaches to the same problem without stepping on each other. Worktrees are git's built-in answer to exactly this, but they're annoying to manage manually. Baking them into tile creation makes the whole workflow disappear into the UI.

Mental model
A tile in "worktree mode" has:

A source repository (the "real" repo the user opened)
A worktree path (somewhere under a managed directory, e.g. ~/.focusterm/worktrees/<repo>-<tile_id>/)
A branch (either auto-created like focusterm/tile-abc123 or user-named)
A base reference (what the worktree was created from — usually HEAD, a named branch, or a specific commit)
The tile's PTY has its CWD set to the worktree path. Everything else — the shell, Claude Code, git commands — just works, because from the process's perspective it's in a normal git repository.

The lifecycle
On tile creation with worktree enabled:

1. User toggles "worktree" when creating a tile in a repo
2. Generate branch name (default: focusterm/{workspace-label}-{short-id})
3. Run: git -C <repo> worktree add <worktree-path> -b <branch> <base-ref>
4. Spawn PTY with CWD = <worktree-path>
5. Store worktree metadata in tile state
During tile life:

Tile just works like a normal terminal in a repo
Optionally surface git status in the UI (changed files count on the tile, branch name in the strip card)
On tile close:

Check for uncommitted changes
If clean: prompt to merge back / push / discard / keep worktree
If dirty: warn loudly, default to keeping the worktree so nothing is lost
Run git worktree remove only if user confirms
Why this is tractable
You don't implement git. You shell out to git as a subprocess for the structural operations. The git2 crate is tempting and you might reach for it for status queries (it's faster than shelling out for repeated calls), but for worktree creation/removal, subprocess calls to the system git are safer — they handle every edge case git itself handles, including hooks, config, and weird repo layouts. Correctness beats a few milliseconds.

A minimal worktree manager:

rust
// focusterm-core/src/worktree.rs

pub struct WorktreeConfig {
    pub source_repo: PathBuf,
    pub branch_name: String,
    pub base_ref: String,  // "HEAD", "main", "abc123", etc.
    pub cleanup_on_close: CleanupPolicy,
}

pub enum CleanupPolicy {
    Always,          // remove worktree on tile close (if clean)
    Never,           // keep worktree around
    Prompt,          // ask user on close
}

pub struct Worktree {
    pub config: WorktreeConfig,
    pub path: PathBuf,
    pub created_at: SystemTime,
}

impl Worktree {
    pub fn create(config: WorktreeConfig, base_dir: &Path) -> Result<Self> {
        let worktree_path = base_dir.join(format!(
            "{}-{}", 
            config.source_repo.file_name().unwrap().to_string_lossy(),
            random_id(6),
        ));
        
        let output = Command::new("git")
            .arg("-C").arg(&config.source_repo)
            .arg("worktree").arg("add")
            .arg(&worktree_path)
            .arg("-b").arg(&config.branch_name)
            .arg(&config.base_ref)
            .output()?;
        
        if !output.status.success() {
            return Err(WorktreeError::GitFailed(
                String::from_utf8_lossy(&output.stderr).into_owned()
            ));
        }
        
        Ok(Worktree {
            config,
            path: worktree_path,
            created_at: SystemTime::now(),
        })
    }
    
    pub fn status(&self) -> Result<WorktreeStatus> {
        // git -C <path> status --porcelain=v2 --branch
        // parse output for dirty/clean, ahead/behind, staged counts
    }
    
    pub fn remove(&self, force: bool) -> Result<()> {
        let mut cmd = Command::new("git");
        cmd.arg("-C").arg(&self.config.source_repo)
           .arg("worktree").arg("remove");
        if force { cmd.arg("--force"); }
        cmd.arg(&self.path);
        
        let output = cmd.output()?;
        if !output.status.success() {
            return Err(WorktreeError::GitFailed(/* ... */));
        }
        Ok(())
    }
}
The gotchas specific to worktrees
Detecting the repo root. When a user enables worktree mode for a tile, you need to know what repo they're in. Run git -C <cwd> rev-parse --show-toplevel and use the output. If it fails, the tile is not in a repo — surface that error and don't show the worktree toggle.

Branch naming collisions. If the user creates a tile, closes it without cleanup, then creates another with the same default name, git worktree add -b will fail. Either include a short random suffix in auto-generated names (what I'd do) or detect collision and increment.

Submodules. If the parent repo has submodules, git worktree add doesn't automatically init them in the new worktree. If you care, run git submodule update --init --recursive after creation. For v1, document the limitation and move on.

Hooks. .git/hooks is not shared across worktrees — each worktree has its own hooks directory. If a user's team relies on pre-commit hooks installed via some tool, they'll need to reinstall in the worktree. This is a git quirk, not yours to fix, but worth mentioning in your docs.

Disk space. Worktrees share git objects (that's the whole point), but working files are separate copies. Six worktrees of a 500MB repo = 3GB of working files. Not huge, but worth surfacing in the UI when worktrees accumulate.

Cleanup of orphaned worktrees. If your app crashes mid-session, worktrees are left behind. Git knows about them via git worktree list — so on startup, scan for worktrees your app created (recognizable by path prefix or a marker file you drop) and offer to clean them up. Don't auto-delete; users might have uncommitted work.

Merging back. The UX question: when a user is "done" with a worktree tile, how do they get their work back into the main branch? Options range from "do it yourself in the other tile" (simplest) to a guided merge/PR flow (complicated). I'd start with a "Copy branch name" button and let users handle merging in their main tile. Add automation later if there's demand.

UI integration
In the tile creation flow (a "+" button or Cmd+T), show a small toggle: "Create as worktree". When enabled, reveal:

Branch name (editable, with a sensible default)
Base branch dropdown (populated from git branch -a)
On the tile itself, show a subtle branch indicator — something like ⎇ focusterm/tile-abc123 in a corner, maybe with dirty state (● if uncommitted changes). In the strip card, include the branch name if the worktree is the notable thing about that tile.

